=========================================
std::thread (C++11) – MULTITHREADING NOTES
=========================================

1. What is std::thread?
-----------------------
- std::thread is a C++11 library feature for creating and managing threads.
- It allows parallel execution of functions.
- Defined in <thread> header.

Header:
#include <thread>

-----------------------------------------

2. Basic Example
----------------

#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
using namespace std;

void printHello() {
    cout << "Hello from thread\n";
}

int main() {
    thread t(printHello); // create thread

    t.join(); // wait for thread to finish

    cout << "Main thread\n";
}

-----------------------------------------

3. Why std::thread is needed?
-----------------------------
Before C++11:
- No standard way for multithreading in C++
- Platform-specific APIs (POSIX threads, Windows threads)

With std::thread:
- Portable (cross-platform)
- Easier syntax
- Integrated with C++ standard library

-----------------------------------------

4. join() vs detach()
---------------------

join():
- Main thread waits for child thread to finish
- Ensures proper synchronization

detach():
- Thread runs independently in background
- No control over its completion

Example:

thread t(func);
t.detach();  // runs independently

⚠️ Warning:
- Detached threads may cause undefined behavior if main exits early

-----------------------------------------

5. Passing Arguments to Thread
-----------------------------

#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
using namespace std;

void add(int a, int b) {
    cout << a + b << endl;
}

int main() {
    thread t(add, 10, 20);
    t.join();
}

-----------------------------------------

6. Passing by Reference (IMPORTANT)
-----------------------------------

#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
using namespace std;

void update(int &x) {
    x += 10;
}

int main() {
    int val = 5;

    thread t(update, ref(val)); // use std::ref
    t.join();

    cout << val;
}

-----------------------------------------

7. Lambda with std::thread
--------------------------

thread t([](){
    cout << "Thread using lambda\n";
});

t.join();

-----------------------------------------

8. Thread Lifecycle
-------------------
1. Created
2. Running
3. Finished
4. Joined / Detached

-----------------------------------------

9. Hardware Concurrency
-----------------------
- Returns number of supported threads

#include <thread>
cout << thread::hardware_concurrency();

-----------------------------------------

10. Common Problems
-------------------
(a) Race condition
- Multiple threads accessing shared data

(b) Deadlock
- Threads waiting indefinitely for each other

(c) Data inconsistency
- Without synchronization (mutex required)

-----------------------------------------

11. std::thread with class member function
------------------------------------------

class A {
public:
    void show() {
        cout << "Member function thread\n";
    }
};

int main() {
    A obj;
    thread t(&A::show, &obj);
    t.join();
}

-----------------------------------------

12. Best Practices
------------------
- Always join or detach a thread
- Prefer RAII wrappers like std::jthread (C++20)
- Avoid shared data without synchronization
- Use mutex for protection

-----------------------------------------

13. Interview Key Points
------------------------
- Introduced in C++11
- Defined in <thread>
- Supports parallel execution
- join() vs detach() important
- Use std::ref for reference passing
- Requires synchronization for shared data

